AB  - This study examines the predictive impact of weather conditions and electricity demand on hourly spot prices of emissions allowances during the first three phases of the European Union Emissions Trading System (EU ETS) (2005-2019). We propose an original methodology for constructing European-scale electricity demand and weather indices and characterize the relationship between those indices and emissions allowances prices by means of an advanced predictive modeling technique (Extreme Gradient Boosting). Empirical findings assert that electricity demand and the weather variables under study were of importance for estimating EUA prices during the first three phases of the EU ETS, with air temperature and electricity demand being most relevant to emissions allowances prices. Conversely, total precipitation and relative humidity proved to be the least relevant variables to the outcome. The results also indicate that the relationship between emissions allowances prices and their weather-related predictors was not linear in the studied period. The paper contributes to the growing body of literature on the structural determinants of carbon prices in the EU ETS and enhances our understanding of the impact of climate and weather variability - in the provision of renewable energy production - on the most prominent market-based measure to reduce CO2 emissions in Europe.
AB  - 本研究探讨了在欧盟排放交易体系（EU ETS）的前三个阶段（2005-2019 年），天气条件和电力需求对排放配额每小时现货价格的预测影响。 我们提出了构建欧洲范围电力需求和天气指数的原创方法，并通过先进的预测建模技术（极端梯度提升）描述了这些指数与排放配额价格之间的关系。 实证研究结果表明，在欧盟排放交易计划的前三个阶段，电力需求和所研究的天气变量对估算欧盟排放配额价格非常重要，其中气温和电力需求与排放配额价格的关系最为密切。 相反，总降水量和相对湿度被证明是与结果相关性最小的变量。 研究结果还表明，在研究期间，排放配额价格与其天气相关预测因素之间并非线性关系。 这篇论文为越来越多关于欧盟排放交易计划中碳价格结构性决定因素的文献做出了贡献，并加深了我们对气候和天气变化--在提供可再生能源生产方面--对欧洲最主要的基于市场的二氧化碳减排措施的影响的理解。
