AB  - The Clean Development Mechanism (CDM) is a flexible carbon market mechanism managed by the United Nations. The program grants tradable carbon emissions credits (Certified Emission Reductions) for carbon-reducing projects in developing countries. A project can only be admitted to the program if it is not financially profitable, and thus would not take place without the emission credits granted through the CDM. In this paper, we examine how monitoring reduces incentives of companies to bias the reported expected financial viability of potential CDM projects to gain admission to the program. We find that reported rates of return, which are a key factor for admission to the program, tend to be downwardly biased and are negatively associated with the expected benefits stemming from forecasted greenhouse gas reductions. However, monitoring from various sources mitigates some of the distorted incentives and related reporting bias. Furthermore, the monitoring effect becomes much stronger after 2008, when the CDM Executive Board implemented a series of measures to strengthen the additionality testing that provides guidance for program applications.
AB  - 清洁发展机制（CDM）是联合国管理的一个灵活的碳市场机制。 该计划为发展中国家的减碳项目提供可交易的碳排放信用额度（核证减排量）。 一个项目只有在财务上无利可图的情况下才能加入该计划，因此，如果没有清洁发展机制提供的排放额度，该项目就不会实施。 在本文中，我们研究了监督如何减少公司为获得项目准入而在报告的潜在清洁发展机制项目的预期财务可行性方面出现偏差的动机。 我们发现，报告的收益率是加入项目的一个关键因素，但往往存在向下偏差，并且与预测温室气体减排产生的预期收益呈负相关。 然而，来自各种渠道的监督缓解了一些扭曲的激励机制和相关的报告偏差。 此外，2008 年后，清洁发展机制执行理事会采取了一系列措施来加强额外性测试，为项目申请提供指导，因此监测效果变得更加明显。
