AB  - In this study, we introduce an integrated framework for managing the complex interdependence between urban infrastructures and the socioeconomic environment within which it evolves, in pursuit of sustainable and environmentally cleaner urban living. The framework addresses the nature of individual preferences for more sustainable urban infrastructures, and how we can use this knowledge to improve urban form in ways that reduce environmental impacts. Using metropolitan Atlanta as a case study, we developed a survey that focuses on the preferences of Atlanta residents for low-impact development (LID) and transit-oriented development (TOD), with responses collected on the Mechanical Turk crowed-source platform. Using these responses we developed a latent-class residential community choice model for four distinctive classes of respondents that revealed heterogeneous preferences for community amenities. Next, we integrated the results of these individual choices into an agent-based market diffusion model, to predict land-use pattern, and to explore policies that drive greater adoption of more compact development. Finally, we used the results of this data collection and modelling to estimate the carbon emission reduction potentials from more compact development driven by LID and TOD. In the future, we will continuously refine the steps and address the issues including survey sample bias to make the framework more reliable and useful for sustainable urban infrastructure planning, design and implementation.
AB  - 在本研究中，我们介绍了一个综合框架，用于管理城市基础设施与社会经济环境之间复杂的相互依存关系，以追求可持续的、更环保的城市生活。 该框架涉及个人对更具可持续性的城市基础设施的偏好性质，以及我们如何利用这些知识来改善城市形态，从而减少对环境的影响。 我们以亚特兰大大都市为案例，开展了一项调查，重点关注亚特兰大居民对低影响开发（LID）和公交导向开发（TOD）的偏好，并在 Mechanical Turk 众包平台上收集回复。 利用这些回复，我们为四个不同类别的受访者开发了一个潜类住宅社区选择模型，揭示了他们对社区设施的不同偏好。 接下来，我们将这些个人选择的结果整合到一个基于代理的市场扩散模型中，以预测土地使用模式，并探索推动采用更紧凑发展的政策。 最后，我们利用这些数据收集和建模的结果，估算了由 LID 和 TOD 驱动的更紧凑型发展的碳减排潜力。 未来，我们将不断完善这些步骤，并解决包括调查样本偏差在内的问题，使该框架更加可靠，更有助于可持续城市基础设施的规划、设计和实施。
